This is a special case with `cmd`. I previously only noticed that using `/` here would cause an error, but I didn’t expect it to behave this strangely: `:terminal` stops working, it creates a `.exe` directory and then exits immediately. 
I also tried a small demo and was able to reproduce :

<details><summary>demo</summary>
<p>

```c
#include <windows.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    STARTUPINFOA si;
    PROCESS_INFORMATION pi;

    ZeroMemory(&si, sizeof(si));
    ZeroMemory(&pi, sizeof(pi));
    si.cb = sizeof(si);

    char *file = NULL;
    char cmdline[] = "C:/WINDOWS/system32/cmd.exe";
    BOOL ok = CreateProcessA(
        file,
        cmdline,
        NULL, NULL,
        FALSE,
        0,
        NULL,
        NULL,
        &si,
        &pi
    );

    if (!ok) {
        printf("CreateProcess failed: %lu\n", GetLastError());
        return 1;
    }

    printf("Started PID=%lu\n", pi.dwProcessId);

    WaitForSingleObject(pi.hProcess, INFINITE);

    CloseHandle(pi.hProcess);
    CloseHandle(pi.hThread);
    return 0;
}
```
```pwsh
issue-36112> .\demo.exe
Started PID=544
issue-36112> .\demo.exe
Started PID=9956
A subdirectory or file .exe already exists.
```

</p>
</details> 


need some more time to figure out the root cause. If we don't want to use backslash here, we can pass fullpath of `cmd.exe` to `lpApplicationName`, and just use `cmd.exe` here.

